04644nam a22005535i 9780773562622DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19901990xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735626227 a10.1515/97807735626222doi  a(DE-B1597)655144  a(OCoLC)732600721  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aHIS0220002bisacsh1 aCohen, Derek, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJewish Presences in English Literature /cDerek Cohen, Deborah Heller. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1990] 4cÂ©1990  a1 online resource (152 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tDangerous Innocence -- tShylock and the Idea of the Jew -- tThe Outcast as Villain and Victim: Jews in Dickens's Oliver Twist and Our Mutual Friend -- tConstructing the Contradiction -- tJews and Women in George Eliot's Daniel Deronda -- tThe Jew in James Joyce's Ulysses -- tLiterary Jews and the Breakdown of the Medieval Testamental Pattern -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"The image of the Jew in English literature, as in the Western imagination, has at its base the figure of the Christ-killer. All representations of the Jew in Christian culture are constructed in the light of this irreducible definition." -- from the introduction In a collection of insightful critical essays, Derek Cohen, Deborah Heller, and the contributing authors explore the different ways in which writers of English literature have amplified, varied, or denied this archetypical perception. While the authors approach this subject from diverse perspectives, the essays are unified by an awareness of the common tradition out of which representations of Jews have developed and illustrate the tradition's continuity and modifications. Studying the works of Chaucer, Shakespeare, Dickens, Trollope, George Eliot, Joyce, and a selection of texts from the ninth to the sixteenth century, the essays show how constructs of Jewishness fit into a writer's pre-existing concerns and patterns of representation and how even later, more favourable depictions are over-simplified reactions to this attitude. Some of the authors directly address the question of what constitutes anti-semitism in a literary work. All take into account the social and historical contexts in which the individual works took shape. Their main concern, however, is not to produce a social history but to illustrate how even the greatest writers draw on stereotypes embedded in the popular imagination and to focus on the internal dynamics of individual works, thereby recuperating classical portrayals within a contemporary critical perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aArthur, Ross G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGirling, Harry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeller, Deborah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHeller, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoretsky, Allen C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356262240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773562622423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773562622/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-P